{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627781"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17152"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17152"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.13,0.02,0.04,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76988"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9867"},{"type":"tags","id":"9868"},{"type":"tags","id":"9869"},{"type":"tags","id":"9871"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23049"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76988"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFluid exchange across capillary membranes is governed by Starling forces, which include both hydrostatic and oncotic pressure gradients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary force driving fluid filtration at the arteriolar end of capillaries?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased interstitial oncotic pressure","Decreased interstitial hydrostatic pressure","Increased plasma oncotic pressure","Balanced Starling forces","Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt the arteriolar end of a capillary, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased capillary hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is the predominant force driving fluid filtration. The hydrostatic pressure (approximately 35 mmHg) exceeds the opposing oncotic pressure (approximately 25 mmHg), resulting in net filtration of fluid into the interstitial space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased interstitial oncotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Interstitial oncotic pressure is typically lower than plasma oncotic pressure and does not drive filtration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased interstitial hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - While this exists, it is not the primary force driving filtration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased plasma oncotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - This actually opposes filtration by promoting fluid retention within capillaries\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBalanced Starling forces\u003C/strong\u003E - The forces are not in equilibrium at the arteriolar end, allowing net filtration to occur\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pressure gradient ensures delivery of nutrients to tissues through filtration at the arteriolar end, while excess fluid is reabsorbed at the venular end where oncotic forces predominate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Starling forces determine fluid movement across capillary membranes through the balance of hydrostatic and oncotic pressures.","Net filtration occurs at the arteriolar end of capillaries where hydrostatic pressure exceeds oncotic pressure.","The capillary hydrostatic pressure gradient is the main force driving fluid filtration at the arteriolar end."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62494"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17152"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62494"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T21:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:58:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76988"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","sy